388	workshop_facilitator_info	<div><strong>Karin van Oostrum</strong> from Pretoria, South Africa, has been involved in home education for the past 29 years, together with her late husband Leendert van Oostrum. Their three daughters never attended school.<br>Before her marriage, Karin obtained a BA degree, as well a BA Honours, and a BA Honours in Applied Linguistics. She worked as a lecturer for a while, as a youth worker, and as a translator and editor. She and her late husband, Leendert van Oostrum, were co-founders of the South African Association for Home Schooling in 1992.<br>In 1998 they co-founded the Pestalozzi Trust, the South African legal defence fund for home and civil education, and have since then managed the Trust together. She accompanied Leendert to the GHEC 2012 and 2016. Since Leendert’s death in October 2016 Karin has been appointed manager of the Trust and is responsible for the general and financial administration of the Trust. She also handles telephonic and electronic enquiries on various aspects of homeschooling and offers workshops to veterans and newbies on legal and practical aspects of home education.<br><br><strong>Bouwe van der Eems</strong> and his wife Debbie have been educating their 5 children from 2000 onwards. In 2002 he became involved in homeschool organisations when he became a trustee and treasurer of the Pestalozzi Trust. He also served a number of terms as a member of the executive committee of the Association for Homeschooling and the Cape Home Educators. In 2016, Bouwe became the chairman of the Pestalozzi Trust.<br>In 2011 he and his family established the online platform SAHomeschoolers.Org that aims to be the starting point for people interested in home education to become part of the home education ecosystem. In 2013, SAHomeschoolers.Org joined forces with the Kragdag organisation that organises home education events in South Africa.<br>Bouwe holds an MSC in Electronics Engineering from the University of Stellenbosch and currently works as an enterprise architect in the IT industry.<br><br><strong>Christopher</strong> <strong>Cordeiro</strong> and his wife Michelle have been homeschooling their 5 children since 2002 when they were unable to find a Montessori primary school that was true to their values and the Montessori philosophy. Their homeschooling approach has therefore followed a mix of Montessorian principles and their children’s interests.<br>From the time he was a young boy, who read every book in the library on military history, Christopher has been fascinated by strategy and how better decision making can lead to better outcomes. This interest has served him well in a career that has focused on Strategic Management. His fields of experience cover Marketing, Insurance and Insurance Law, Communications, Sales Management, and more recently Governance. Being able to work from home has allowed Christopher to be the primary home educating parent.<br>In 2017, he founded LearnFree, a volunteer organisation consisting of business people, professionals and academics committed to promoting the quality of education in South Africa through greater freedom in education. LearnFree works primarily by networking between the political, academic, legal and media spheres.<br>Christopher’s diverse fields of interest are reflected in his academic qualifications. He holds a BA (Law) from the University of the Witwatersrand, a Post-Graduate Diploma in Marketing Management (UNISA) and is a Fellow of the Insurance Institute of South Africa. Along with these, he holds a number of lesser qualifications in the fields of business and project management.<br>He consults to and is an advisory Trustee of the Pestalozzi Trust.</div>	Workshop	2	2020-09-30 13:49:01.792068	2020-10-07 16:53:38.513455
