67	about_exhibitor	<div>The Voortrekker Monument is situated in the northern part of South Africa in the Pretoria (Tshwane) region in a 341 ha nature reserve. It is a unique Monument that was built between 1938 and 1949 to commemorate the Pioneer history of Southern Africa and the history of the Afrikaner. The Voortrekker Monument and Nature Reserve was registered as a Section 21 non-profit company in 1993 and is in private ownership. In 2011 it was declared a grade 1 National Heritage Site by the South African Heritage Resources Agency, the first site in Pretoria to be awarded this honour. Today it is the most visited heritage site of its kind in Gauteng and one of the top ten cultural historical visitor attractions in the country. Other attractions on site include Fort Schanskop (Anglo Boer War site), the Heritage Centre, Funda Discovery Centre, replica Zulu hut and various statues and smaller monuments. The site has a variety of venues for hire, a gift shop and restaurant facilities. The Voortrekker Monument also manages the Blood River Heritage Site in KZN.<br><br><br></div>	Company	22	2020-09-09 12:09:54.013638	2020-09-30 07:02:29.221758
63	products_and_services	<div>Briza has strived to serve a niche market with <strong>full-colour, non-fiction books </strong>that treat their subject matter in great depth but without sacrificing<br>accessibility and readability. With the emphasis on botany and natural history, the Briza list has, over the years built a reputation for its high quality<br>production, practical approach and informative content. As a result, our book appeal to both the layman and the more specialist or academic<br>reader.<br><br>At present, its published list comprises <strong>more then 200 titles</strong> and includes definitive <strong>identification guides on medicinal plants, food plants, poisonous<br>plants, indigenous plants, indigenous trees, indigenous garden plants, problem plants, wildflowers and plant groups such as the aloes, acacias and<br>mesembs. </strong>Briza also publishes books on <strong>gardening, ecology, tourism and natural history, including books on mammals, reptiles and birds.<br><br></strong>Briza Publication’s latest innovation is their revolutionary <strong><em>The Talking Dictionary</em></strong> which is the first of its kind, a project that took them more than four years to complete. The <em>The Talking Dictionary</em> is an <strong>audio visual dictionary</strong> that links key words and phrases to full-colour illustrations and then allows you to use the Callfinder to listen to the pronunciation of those words in eight different languages – English, Afrikaans, Sesotho, Sesotho sa Leboa, Setswana, isiZulu, isiXhosa and  Mandarin. <br><br>We have a permanent <strong>sales and marketing team</strong> to assist our authors in promoting their books. Briza has it’s <strong>own warehouse- and distribution department </strong>and we supply product / books to Exclusive Books, Bargain Books, Van Schaik and other leading bookshops. We have our own <strong>online shop</strong>. Briza also supply to other online shops e.g. Takealot.<br><br>Hurry, LB (2020) <strong><em>Abygale Aardvark and her Wildlife Friends Working together for a better life</em></strong><em>. </em>Briza Publications, Pretoria. Soft cover, 280X210mm, 104 pp, illustrated throughout with colour photographs and images.  ISBN 978-920217-72-3.  THIS BOOK WILL BE AVAILABLE SOON.</div><div>Abygale Aardvark and her Wildlife Friends is a carefully researched and invitingly presented book for readers of all ages by well-known South African environmental writer Dr Lynn Hurry. While each of the 20 stories is introduced and commented on by fictional character Abygale Aardvark she leaves the actual story-telling to the real wildlife characters themselves so that Aardvarks, Aardwolfs, Giraffes, Hornbills, Baboons, White-eyes, Impala, Red-billed Oxpeckers, Cape Buffalo, Red-chested Cuckoos and even Honey-Bees and Termites have a chance to tell their stories – of who they are ‘friends’ with and how they work together with ‘for a better life’.  At the back of the book three sections add considerable interest to the book: <em>What’s in a name?</em> is an important section at the back of the book which adds fascination for readers by providing explanations of all the scientific names of the animals in the stories; <em>Make your own cardboard cut-out badges</em><strong> </strong>is an encouragement to readers to get involved with wildlife conservation; and  <em>Abygale’s Glossary</em> which provides simple explanations of some of the words in each story.<br><br></div><div>Every story has a final message – that every animal species, from a sparrow to a crocodile needs the help of everyone if they are to survive into the future and this book is an open invitation for all to participate.<br><br></div>	Company	21	2020-09-09 12:08:37.772243	2020-10-02 11:25:43.681267
