obs/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBdEVFIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--614084361a658e05ebba1a73f4958305501a3618/Untitled%20design%20(7).jpg" filename="Untitled design (7).jpg" filesize="15550" width="500" height="100" previewable="true" presentation="gallery" caption="."></action-text-attachment></div><div><strong>Questions / General comments</strong></div><div> </div><div><strong><em>What about the glossaries in the learners’ textbooks?</em></strong></div><div>These are very useful but do not cross-reference to related words that develop the subject and promote understanding of concept; and are grade-specific, hence do not allow revision of previous years' material; they also do not cover the terms as comprehensively as our dictionaries (which include technical, non-technical and instruction words). </div><div> </div><div><strong><em>Surely learners can "just google it"?</em></strong></div><div>Yes, they can look up a word on the internet; but internet search results often do not relate directly to the use of the word in the curriculum; and getting through to useful information is frustrating and slow. </div>	Company	46	2020-09-25 10:10:35.55753	2020-10-07 18:01:03.561316
