454	introduction	<div>At 16 years old and fascinated with business, Eryquin grew dissatisfied with the fact that the only skills she would learn about entrepreneurship would probably be during, or even after, university. On questioning this, she realized that there must be a better way to approach learning business- and entrepreneurial skills and set out on a journey to find the best solution.</div><div> </div><div>For weeks she carefully planned a business structure and model whereby she could learn these skills and have the philanthropic impact in people’s lives that she wanted. It was time to formulate her business plan.</div><div> </div><div>Charity work forms the basis of the Grade 10’s annual Debutante program. With this in mind Eryquin decided to share the business plan with her teacher in an attempt to structure the year’s Debutante activities. As the teacher unceremoniously threw the business model in the dustbin in the presence of all her classmates, Eryquin realized not many people share the same vision.</div><div> </div><div>After secretly unlocking the class that evening to retrieve the business plan, she decided to dust the plan and not let anyone’s limited vision affect hers. Eryquin concluded that although growth is a vulnerable process, one would risk rebelling against the static and narrow-minded norm to alter it to a place of inspiration, leadership and growth.</div><div> </div><div>Now, at 18 and the youngest person to complete Brené Brown’s Dare To Lead coaching certification in South Africa, Eryquin has found her solution to learning about business - a simulation platform and presents it as part of her non-profit company, the MOR Foundation, founded from the very business plan that she collected from her teacher’s bin.</div>	Company	60	2020-10-07 12:53:52.609084	2020-10-13 09:58:41.1437
